\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Book Twenty Three\uc0\u8232 The Funeral Games for Patroclus\
[Achilles keeps his troops together to mourn Patroclus; Patroclus' ghost visits Achilles, requesting a burial; Achaeans gather wood and prepare Patroclus' funeral pyre; Achilles cuts the hair dedicated to the river Spercheus; Achilles sacrifices animals and humans on Patroclus' pyre; Achilles gets the help of the winds to get the fire to light under Patroclus; Achilles brings out prizes for the Funeral Games, which then take place in series: the chariot race, boxing, wrestling, foot-racing, armed duelling, throwing a weight, archery, and spear throwing; Achilles awards Agamemnon the prize for the last event without any contest]\
Meanwhile, as Trojans were lamenting in the city,\uc0\u8232 Achaeans reached their ships beside the Hellespont.\u8232 There they scattered, each man going to his own ship.\u8232 But Achilles didn\'92t let his Myrmidons disband.\u8232 He spoke out to his warrior companions:\
\'93Fast-riding Myrmidons, trusty comrades,\uc0\u8232 let\'92s not loose our sure-footed horses yet,\u8232 untying them from their chariots. We must go\u8232 with horse and chariot up to Patroclus,\u8232 to mourn for him. For that\'92s a dead man\'92s right.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\u8232 Once we\'92ve had our fill of sorrowful tears,\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\u8232 we\'92ll unyoke our horses, then all eat here.\'94\
At these words, they all began their group lament,\uc0\u8232 led by Achilles. Three times around the body\u8232 they drove their well-groomed horses, mourning as they went.\u8232 Thetis stirred up in them a strong desire to weep.\u8232 Their tears made the sands wet, men\'92s armour, too,\u8232 for they were mourning the loss of a great warrior,\u8232 who\'92d made men flee. Peleus\'92 son led their loud lament,\u8232 placing his man-killing hands on his comrade\'92s chest:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\
\'93Rest in peace, Patroclus, even though\uc0\u8232 you\'92re in Hades house, for I\'92m completing here\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 all I promised you before\'97to drag in Hector,\u8232 then give him to the dogs to eat up raw,\u8232 and cut the throats of twelve young Trojans,\u8232 splendid children, on your funeral pyre,\u8232 in my rage that you\'92ve been slaughtered.\'94\
He finished. Then he continued to dishonour\uc0\u8232 noble Hector, stretching his body out face down\u8232 in the dirt, beside the bier of Menoetius\'92 son.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 Then each man took off his glittering bronze armour.\u8232 They untied their loud-neighing horses and sat down,\u8232 thousands of them, by swift-footed Achilles\'92 ship.\u8232 He prepared a funeral feast to ease their spirits.\u8232 Many sleek oxen bellowed underneath the knife,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\u8232 as they were butchered. Many sheep, bleating goats,\u8232 and white-tusked pigs rich in fat were laid out\u8232 to roast over Hephaestus\'92 fires. All around the corpse,\u8232 blood ran so thick men scooped it up in cupfuls.\
Then Achaean leaders led the swift-footed prince,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\uc0\u8232 son of Peleus, to lord Agamemnon.\u8232 They had trouble convincing him to go there\'97\u8232 his heart was still so angry for his comrade.\u8232 Reaching Agamemnon\'92s hut, they issued orders\u8232 for clear-voiced heralds to heat up a large cauldron,\u8232 to see if they could persuade Peleus\'92 son to wash,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\u8232 to rinse off the spattered blood. In his stubbornness,\u8232 he refused to do that, swearing this oath:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93By Zeus,\uc0\u8232 highest and most excellent of all gods,\u8232 it\'92s not right that water touch my head,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\u8232 until I\'92ve laid Patroclus on his fire,\u8232 piled up a burial mound, and shaved my hair,\u8232 since such grief will never reach my heart\u8232 a second time, not while I still remain\u8232 among the living. But for the moment,\u8232 let\'92s agree to dine, though I hate to eat.\u8232 In the morning, Agamemnon, king of men,\u8232 you must urge men to gather wood, arrange\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\u8232 all things required for a man who\'92s died,\u8232 as he goes below to murky darkness,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\u8232 so tireless fires can cremate him quickly\u8232 and remove him from our sight. Then soldiers\u8232 can resume their duties.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Achilles spoke.\uc0\u8232 They all listened to him and readily agreed.\u8232 Men all rushed out, prepared a meal, and dined,\u8232 eating to their heart\'92s content and sharing equally.\u8232 Once they\'92d satisfied their need for food and drink,\u8232 each man returned to his own hut to get some rest.\u8232 But Peleus\'92 son lay moaning loudly on the shore,\u8232 beside the crashing sea, with many Myrmidons,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\u8232 in an open spot, where waves washed up on shore.\u8232 When sleep took hold of him and eased his aching heart\u8232 by sweetly flowing round him\'97for his splendid limbs\u8232 were tired out from chasing after Hector\u8232 by wind-swept Ilion\'97then poor Patroclus\u8232 came to him as a ghost, looking exactly like him\u8232 in all respects\'97in stature, handsome eyes, and voice.\u8232 He stood there, above Achilles\'92 head, body covered\u8232 with the same clothes he used to wear over his skin.\u8232 The ghost spoke to Achilles, saying:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93You\'92re asleep, Achilles.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\uc0\u8232 You\'92ve forgotten me. While I was alive,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\u8232 you never did neglect me. But now I\'92m dead.\u8232 So bury me as quickly as you can.\u8232 Then I can pass through the gates of Hades.\u8232 The spirits, ghosts of the dead, keep me away.\u8232 They don\'92t let me join them past the river.\u8232 So I wander aimlessly round Hades\'92 home\u8232 by its wide gates. Give me your hand, I beg you,\u8232 for I\'92ll never come again from Hades,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 once you\'92ve given me what\'92s due, my funeral fire.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\u8232 We\'92ll no more sit together making plans,\u8232 separated from our dear companions.\u8232 The jaws of dreadful Fate are gaping for me,\u8232 ready to consume me\'97my destiny\u8232 from the day that I was born. You, too,\u8232 godlike Achilles, you have your own fate,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\u8232 to die under the walls of wealthy Troy.\u8232 I\'92ll say one more thing, one last request,\u8232 if you will listen. Achilles, don\'92t lay your bones\u8232 apart from mine. Let them remain together,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\u8232 just as they were when we grew up in your home,\u8232 once Menoetius brought me as a youngster\u8232 into your land from Opoeis, for I\'92d done\u8232 a dreadful murder on that day I killed\u8232 Amphidamas\'92 son, in my foolishness.\u8232 I didn\'92t mean to, but I was enraged\u8232 over some game of dice. Horseman Peleus\u8232 welcomed me into his home, raised me\u8232 with love, then made me your attendant.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\u8232 So let the same container hold our bones,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\u8232 that gold two-handled jar your mother gave you.\'94\
Swift-footed Achilles then said in reply:\
\'93Dear friend, why have you come to me here,\uc0\u8232 telling me everything I need to do?\u8232 I\'92ll carry out all these things for you,\u8232 attend to your request. But come closer.\u8232 Let\'92s hold each other one short moment more,\u8232 enjoying a shared lament together.\'94\
Saying this, Achilles reached out with his arms,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\uc0\u8232 but he grasped nothing. The spirit had departed,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 going underground like vapour, muttering faintly.\u8232 Achilles jumped up in amazement, clapped his hands,\u8232 and then spoke out in sorrow:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93How sad!\uc0\u8232 It seems that even in Hades\'92 house,\u8232 some spirit or ghost remains, but our being\u8232 is not there at all. For this entire night\u8232 the ghost of poor Patroclus stood beside me,\u8232 weeping, lamenting, asking me to do things,\u8232 in every detail amazingly like him.\'94\
Achilles\'92 words stirred the desire to keep mourning\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\uc0\u8232 in all of them. When rose-fingered Dawn appeared,\u8232 they were still lamenting by that cheerless corpse.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\
Then mighty Agamemnon sent out men and mules,\uc0\u8232 from huts in every quarter, to gather wood.\u8232 The man who supervised was Meriones,\u8232 brave attendant to kind Idomeneus. They set off,\u8232 grasping axes to chop wood and well-woven rope.\u8232 The mules went on ahead. The men kept going,\u8232 up and down the slopes, sometimes tracking sideways,\u8232 sometimes doubling back, till they reached Ida\'92s foothills\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\u8232 with their many springs. At once they started working\'97\u8232 cutting high-branched oak trees with their long-edged bronze.\u8232 Men worked hard, falling each tree with a mighty crash.\u8232 Achaeans then split the trees into convenient lengths,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 tied logs behind the mules, whose feet ploughed up the ground\u8232 as they strained through thick underbrush towards the plain.\u8232 Woodsmen all carried logs as well, under orders\u8232 from Meriones, attendant to kind Idomeneus.\u8232 Men threw these logs down in a line along the shore,\u8232 where Achilles planned a massive burial mound\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0150\u8232 for Patroclus and himself. When they\'92d piled up\u8232 immense amounts of wood on every side, they sat\u8232 all together there and waited. Then Achilles\u8232 quickly told war-loving Myrmidons to dress in bronze,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\u8232 ordering each man to get his horses harnessed\u8232 in their chariots. They leapt up to put on armour.\u8232 The warriors and charioteers climbed in their chariots\u8232 and moved out first. Then came the men on foot\u8232 in their thousands. In the middle, his companions\u8232 bore Patroclus, whose corpse they covered with the hair\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0160\u8232 they\'92d cut from their own heads and thrown onto the body.\u8232 Godlike Achilles came behind them, cradling\u8232 Patroclus\'92 head and grieving. For he was sending\u8232 down to Hades\'92 home a comrade without equal.\u8232 When they reached the spot Achilles chose for them,\u8232 they set the body down and quickly piled up wood\u8232 as he directed. Then swift-footed lord Achilles\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[140]\u8232 thought of something. Standing some distance from the pyre,\u8232 he cut a lock of his own fair hair, one he\'92d grown\u8232 as a rich offering to the river Spercheus.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0170\u8232 Looking out over the wine-dark sea, he spoke out\u8232 in passionate distress:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Spercheus, my father Peleus\uc0\u8232 promised you that, once I came back home\u8232 to my dear native land, I\'92d cut my hair\u8232 for you, then make a holy sacrifice,\u8232 offering up fifty uncastrated rams\u8232 to your waters, where you have your own estate\u8232 and fragrant altars. That oath was useless.\u8232 It\'92s what the old man swore, but you failed\u8232 to bring about what he desired. So now,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0180\u8232 since I\'92ll not be returning home again,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[150]\u8232 let me give this lock to warrior Patroclus\u8232 to carry with him.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Having said these words,\uc0\u8232 Achilles placed his hair in the hands of his dear comrade,\u8232 stirring up in each of them desire to lament.\u8232 Now they would have mourned till sunset, but Achilles\u8232 soon got up and said to Agamemnon:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Son of Atreus,\uc0\u8232 Achaean troops will listen to your words\u8232 more than to anyone. Men can grieve too much.\u8232 So dismiss them from the pyre for now.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0190\u8232 Tell them to prepare a meal. Those of us\u8232 with special cause to mourn will take care of this.\u8232 But let the leaders remain here with us.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[160]\
When Agamemnon, king of men, heard these words,\uc0\u8232 he quickly sent the troops off to their balanced ships.\u8232 The chief mourners stayed behind. They piled up wood,\u8232 making a square pyre, each side one hundred feet in length.\u8232 On that pyre\'92s highest point they laid out the corpse,\u8232 hearts full of sorrow. Then, in front of the pyre,\u8232 they flayed and made ready many sturdy sheep\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0200\u8232 and shambling cattle with twisting horns. From all these,\u8232 great-hearted Achilles took the fat, using it\u8232 to cover up the corpse from head to foot, piling\u8232 skinned carcasses around it. Next, he placed on top\u8232 two-handled jars of oil and honey, leaning them\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[170]\u8232 against the bier. Then, crying with grief, Achilles\u8232 threw four strong-necked horses quickly on the pyre.\u8232 Patroclus had owned nine dogs who ate beside his table.\u8232 Slitting the throats of two of them, Achilles\u8232 tossed them on the pyre. Then, with his bronze, he butchered\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0210\u8232 those twelve noble sons of the courageous Trojans,\u8232 his feelings grimly set on this atrocity.\u8232 After that, he lit the fire to work its iron force\u8232 and burn up everything. With a groan he called out,\u8232 addressing his companion:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Rest in peace,\uc0\u8232 Patroclus, though you\'92re in Hades\'92 house.\u8232 For I\'92m now completing everything\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[180]\u8232 I promised you before. Flames will burn\u8232 twelve noble sons of great-hearted Trojans,\u8232 all cremated with you. But as for Hector,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0220\u8232 Priam\'92s son, I\'92ll not feed him to the fire,\u8232 but to the dogs.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Achilles made this threat,\uc0\u8232 but dogs would not touch Hector. For Aphrodite,\u8232 Zeus\'92 daughter, kept them away, day and night.\u8232 She covered him with immortal oil of roses,\u8232 so Achilles would not wear away his body\u8232 by dragging him around. Phoebus Apollo\u8232 brought a dark cloud from the sky across the plain,\u8232 shadowing the entire place where Hector lay,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[190]\u8232 to stop Sun\'92s power from shrivelling up the flesh\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0230\u8232 on limbs and sinews.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0But now the pyre of dead Patroclus\uc0\u8232 would not catch fire. So swift-footed Achilles\u8232 thought of something else. Standing away from the pyre,\u8232 he prayed to the two winds\'97Boreas of the north,\u8232 Zephyrus of the west\'97promising fine offerings.\u8232 Pouring frequent libations from a golden cup,\u8232 he begged them to come quickly to ignite the wood,\u8232 so flames might incinerate the corpses\'a0\'a0quickly.\u8232 Hearing his prayer, Iris at once took his message\u8232 to the winds, who were feasting all together\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0240\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[200]\u8232 in blustery West Wind\'92s home. Iris raced up there,\u8232 then stood on the stone threshold. Their eyes soon saw her.\u8232 They all jumped up, each one inviting her to sit\u8232 beside him. Iris declined their invitation,\u8232 saying to them:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93I can\'92t sit down. I must return\uc0\u8232 to Oceanus\'92 stream, back in the land\u8232 of Ethiopians, where there\'92s a sacrifice\u8232 to the immortals. I\'92d like to be there\u8232 for that sacred feast. But now Achilles\u8232 prays that North Wind and loud West Wind will come.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0250\u8232 He\'92s promising you splendid offerings\u8232 to stir the flames, so they burn up the pyre\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[210]\u8232 where Patroclus lies, whom all Achaea mourns.\'94\
After saying this, Iris left. The two winds rose up.\uc0\u8232 With an astounding roar, driving clouds before them,\u8232 they quickly stormed across the sea, whipping up waves\u8232 with their howling breath. They came to fertile Troy,\u8232 then fell upon that pyre. The fire crackled up\u8232 into a prodigious blaze. All night long they howled,\u8232 blowing their shrill blasts together on the flames.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0260\u8232 And all night long with a two-handled cup in hand\u8232 swift Achilles kept drawing wine from a golden bowl\u8232 and pouring it upon the earth, soaking the ground\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[220]\u8232 and calling on the spirit of poor Patroclus.\u8232 Just as a father mourns his son, when he burns his bones,\u8232 his newly married son, whose death brings parents\u8232 dreadful sorrow\'97that\'92s how Achilles kept crying then,\u8232 as he burned his companion\'92s bones, dragging himself\u8232 round and round the pyre, lamenting endlessly.\
But at that hour when the Morning Star appears,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0270\uc0\u8232 announcing that light is coming to the earth,\u8232 the star after which Dawn in her yellow robe\u8232 moves out across the sea, by then the fire was dying.\u8232 The flames went out. So the winds returned once more,\u8232 back to their homes, going across the Thracian Sea,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[230]\u8232 where a seething storm roared out. Then Peleus\'92 son,\u8232 moving away from the smouldering pyre, lay down\u8232 exhausted. Sweet Sleep quickly slipped around him.\u8232 But then the troops came up with Agamemnon,\u8232 all together. The noise they made, as they marched in,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0280\u8232 woke up Achilles. Sitting bolt upright, he said:\
\'93Sons of Atreus and you other leaders\uc0\u8232 of Achaean forces, you must first douse\u8232 the smouldering pyre with gleaming wine\'97\u8232 everything the powerful flames have touched.\u8232 Then we\'92ll collect bones from Patroclus,\u8232 Menoetius\'92 son, separating them with care\u8232 from all the rest. They\'92re easy to distinguish,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[240]\u8232 for he lay in the centre of the pyre\'97\u8232 the others burned some distance from him\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0290\u8232 on the edges, the humans and the horses.\u8232 Let\'92s place his bones inside a golden urn,\u8232 in a double layer of fat, until the time\u8232 I myself am hiding there in Hades.\u8232 I\'92m asking you to build a burial mound,\u8232 nothing excessive\'97what seems appropriate.\u8232 You Achaeans must build it high and wide,\u8232 but later, once I\'92m gone, those who still remain\u8232 beside our ships with many oars.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Once Achilles spoke,\uc0\u8232 they did as the swift-footed son of Peleus wished.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0300\u8232 First, they doused the smoking pyre with gleaming wine,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[250]\u8232 wherever flames had reached or ash was deep.\u8232 Weeping, they picked the white bones of their comrade out\u8232 and put them in a double layer of fat inside a golden urn.\u8232 They placed the urn under soft linen in a hut.\u8232 Then they traced out the dimensions of a mound,\u8232 using stones to mark its base around the pyre,\u8232 and then piled earth on top.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0When they\'92d made the mound,\uc0\u8232 they started to return. But Achilles checked them,\u8232 keeping soldiers there. He asked them to sit down\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0310\u8232 in a wide group. Then he brought prizes from his ship\'97\u8232 cauldrons, tripods, horses, mules, powerful oxen,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[260]\u8232 as well as fine-dressed women and grey iron.\
