\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Sons of Atreus,\uc0\u8232 you other well-armed Achaean warriors,\u8232 these prizes lie set out here for a contest\u8232 among the charioteers. If Achaeans\u8232 were now hosting these games for someone else,\u8232 then I myself would surely win first prize\u8232 and take it to my hut, since, as you know,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0330\u8232 my horses are far better than the rest,\u8232 for they\'92re immortal, Poseidon\'92s gift\u8232 to Peleus, my father, who gave them to me.\u8232 But I and my sure-footed horses now\u8232 will stand down, for they\'92ve lost their charioteer,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[280]\u8232 a strong, brave man, so kind he\'92d often pour\u8232 soft oil all through their manes, while washing them\u8232 in clean water. They stand there mourning him,\u8232 manes trailing on the ground. So they won\'92t race.\u8232 Their hearts feel too much grief. But you others,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0340\u8232 get yourselves prepared all through the camp,\u8232 any Achaean who has faith in his own horses\u8232 and his well-made chariot.\'94\
